# Supabase Usage

## Pick the right client factory

| Context | Import |
|---------|--------|
| `'use client'` component | `import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase'` |
| Server Component / Route Handler | `import { createServerSupabaseClient } from '@/lib/supabase-server'` |
| `src/proxy.ts` | uses `createServerClient` from `@supabase/ssr` with a NextRequest cookie adapter (already wired) |

## Env vars (fallback order)

Supabase key is read as: `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY` first, then `NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY`.

```ts
const key =
  process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY ??
  process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY!;
```

Support both schemes in any new server-side code.

## NEVER use the service-role key

This app does NOT use `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`. All access is controlled by **Row Level Security** in `supabase/schema.sql`. If you think you need the service role, you almost certainly need a new RLS policy instead.

## Schema changes

When adding/modifying tables:
1. Update `supabase/schema.sql` (table + RLS policies + storage buckets if needed).
2. Update the matching TypeScript type in `src/types/index.ts`.
3. Document the migration SQL the user has to run in Supabase SQL Editor.
